Task 1: Domain Analysis (5 marks)¶

Given the business domain and the data overview presented (in the assessment paper), provide a brief description of

  • the business problem and its significance to the relevant sector;
  • the link between the business problem and the field of data science;
  • the main areas of investigation; and
  • potential ideas and solutions.

Word Limit: 300 words

Answer:

The NHS holds huge amounts of data related to patients, healthcare professionals, and healthcare facilities. However the problem arises when this data resides across multiple files making it difficult to efficiently retrieve, analyse and draw insights efficiently. Addressing this problem would significantly improve healthcare delivery, optimise resource allocation, and enhance patient outcomes, which are key priorities in the healthcare sector.

Data science provides the tools to address this problem by transforming raw, unstructured data into actionable insights. Techniques such as data processing, data exploration, and predictive analytics using machine learning can help support the NHS at achieving a more efficient, effective, and patient-centred healthcare system, with data-informed decisions.

My project will focus on 3 main areas, aimed at supporting hospital administrators, policymakers and medical professionals. First, I will explore patterns in patient readmissions, which may indicate incomplete or ineffective care. These insights can help hospital administrators improve care pathways and optimise resource planning. Second, I will compare patient outcomes between NHS and private hospitals, offering insights to policymakers to evaluate NHS hospital quality and allocate resources effectively. Third, I aim to identify high-risk patients to support medical professionals to intervene earlier, potentially reducing complications and improving patient outcomes.

To address these areas, I will first build an efficient database that reduces data redundancy and improves query performance. I propose developing a predictive model for patient readmission using medical history and visit patterns, and design a clustering model to segment patients by risk levels, allowing NHS staff to prioritise care more effectively. I also aim at using inferential statistics to compare one aspect of patient outcomes, surgery success rates, between NHS hospital and private hospital type.

1) Normalising Appointments_data table

Primary key: Composite primary key = {appointment_ID, patient_ID, emergency_contact_address, department_ID, hospital_ID, {professional_role, professional_name, department_ID}}

1NF:

  • Rule: All attributes must be atomic
  • Given table in Appointment_data.csv has all atomic values, so it's already in 1NF.

2NF:

Functional dependencies:

  • FD1: appointment_ID -> (functionally determines) -> {patient_ID, appointment_data, appointment_time, appointment_status, proffesional_name, proffesional_role, department_ID}
  • FD2: patient_ID -> (functionally determines) -> {patient_name, patient_date_of_birth, patient_gender, patient_address, patient_preffered_hospital_ID, patient_preffered_pharmacy_ID, patient_preffered_insurance_provider}
  • FD3: emergency_contact_phone -> (functionally determines) -> {emergency_contact_relationship, emergency_contact_name, emergency_contact_phone, emergency_contact_address}
  • FD4: hospital_ID -> (functionally determines) -> {hospital_name, hospital_location}
  • FD5: department_ID -> (functionally determines) -> {hospital_ID, department_name, head_of_department}

To be in 2NF, every non-primary key column should be fully functionally dependent upon all the columns that make up the primary key. So, every non-primary key columns must not have any partial functional dependency. From FD 1 - 5, we can see that there are several non primary key attributes dependent on a proper subset of the primary key (partial dependecy). So, the table is not in 2NF.

The corresponding 2NF consists of the following 6 tables:

3NF:

In order to be in 3NF, non non prime attribute should be transitiviely dependent on the primary key. From the 2NF tables, there exists transitive dependencies in the following tables:

Department table:

Appointment table:

Part c) Implement 3NF schema in SQLite database

SQL statements used in SQLite to create the following tables:

Create appointment table

CREATE TABLE appointment ( appointment_ID TEXT PRIMARY KEY, patient_ID TEXT, appointment_time TEXT, appointment_status TEXT, appointment_date TEXT, professional_name TEXT, professional_role TEXT, department_ID TEXT, FOREIGN KEY (professional_role, professional_name, department_ID) REFERENCES professional(professional_role, professional_name, department_ID) );

INSERT INTO appointment SELECT appointment_ID, patient_id, appointment_time, appointment_status, appointment_date, professional_name, professional_role, department_ID FROM appointments_data WHERE appointment_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY appointment_ID;

Create patient table:

CREATE TABLE patient AS SELECT patient_ID, patient_name, patient_date_of_birth, patient_gender, patient_address, patient_preferred_hospital_ID, patient_preferred_pharmacy_ID, patient_preferred_insurance_provider from appointments_data WHERE patient_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY patient_ID

Create hospital table

CREATE TABLE hospital AS SELECT hospital_ID, hospital_name, hospital_location from appointments_data WHERE hospital_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY hospital_ID

Create department table

CREATE TABLE department AS SELECT department_ID, department_name, head_of_department, hospital_ID from appointments_data WHERE department_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY department_ID

Create Professional table

CREATE TABLE professional AS SELECT DISTINCT professional_role, professional_name, department_ID from appointments_data WHERE professional_role IS NOT NULL AND professional_name IS NOT NULL AND department_ID IS NOT NULL;

Create emergency contact table

CREATE TABLE emergencyContact AS SELECT emergency_contact_phone, emergency_contact_relationship, emergency_contact_name, emergency_contact_address from appointments_data WHERE emergency_contact_address IS NOT NULL GROUP BY emergency_contact_address;

Create patient-emergency contact table

CREATE TABLE patientEmergency AS SELECT DISTINCT patient_ID, emergency_contact_address from appointments_data WHERE patient_ID IS NOT NULL AND emergency_contact_address IS NOT NULL;

Create pharmacy table

CREATE TABLE pharmacy AS SELECT pharmacy_ID, pharmacy_name, pharmacy_location, pharmacy_contact, pharmacy_email, pharmacy_operating_hours, pharmacy_manager_name, pharmacy_website, pharmacy_services_offered from prescription_billing_insurance_data WHERE pharmacy_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY pharmacy_ID;

Create mediction table

CREATE TABLE medication AS SELECT medication_ID, medication_name, manufacturer, medication_dosage_form, medication_strength, medication_price from prescription_billing_insurance_data WHERE medication_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY medication_ID;

Create insurance provider table

CREATE TABLE insuranceProvider AS SELECT insurance_provider_ID, insurance_provider_name, insurance_provider_contact, insurance_provider_coverage_type from prescription_billing_insurance_data WHERE insurance_provider_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY insurance_provider_ID;

Create Prescription Detail Table

CREATE TABLE prescriptionDetail AS SELECT prescription_detail_ID, medication_dosage, medication_quantity, total_medication_billing_amount, dosage_start_date, dosage_end_date, prescription_ID, medication_ID from prescription_billing_insurance_data WHERE prescription_detail_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY prescription_detail_ID;

Create surgery table

CREATE TABLE surgery AS SELECT surgery_ID, surgery_professional_ID, patient_ID, surgery_hospital_ID, surgery_date, surgery_type, surgery_notes, surgery_post_operative_care, surgery_outcome from medical_surgeries_data WHERE surgery_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY surgery_ID;

Create test table

CREATE TABLE test AS SELECT test_ID, test_recommended_by_professional_ID, test_name, test_results, test_date, lab_ID, test_billing_type, patient_ID from medical_tests_data WHERE test_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY test_ID;

Create lab table

CREATE TABLE lab AS SELECT lab_ID, lab_name, lab_location, lab_type, lab_contact from medical_tests_data WHERE lab_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY lab_ID;

Create service billing ID

CREATE TABLE serviceBilling AS SELECT service_billing_ID, service_billing_amount, service_billing_amount_paid, service_billing_payment_date, service_billing_payment_status, appointment_ID, surgery_ID, test_ID from service_billing_insurance_data WHERE service_billing_ID IS NOT NULL GROUP BY service_billing_ID;

Create claim table

CREATE TABLE claim AS SELECT DISTINCT p.claim_id, p.claim_status, p.claim_status_reason, p.claim_amount, p.approved_amount, p.claim_date, p.approval_date, p.insurance_provider_ID, p.prescription_detail_ID, NULL AS service_billing_ID FROM prescription_billing_insurance_data p WHERE p.claim_id IS NOT NULL

UNION

SELECT DISTINCT s.claim_id, s.claim_status, s.claim_status_reason, s.claim_amount, s.approved_amount, s.claim_date, s.approval_date, s.insurance_provider_ID, NULL AS prescription_detail_ID,
s.service_billing_ID FROM service_billing_insurance_data s WHERE s.claim_id IS NOT NULL;

Create medical records table

CREATE TABLE medicalRecords ( record_ID TEXT, diagnosis TEXT, notes TEXT, appointment_ID TEXT, surgery_ID TEXT, test_ID TEXT, patient_ID TEXT );

INSERT INTO medicalRecords (record_ID, diagnosis, notes, appointment_ID, surgery_ID, test_ID, patient_ID) SELECT record_ID, diagnosis, notes, appointment_ID, NULL AS surgery_ID, NULL AS test_ID, patient_ID FROM medical_appointments_data WHERE record_ID IS NOT NULL

UNION

SELECT record_ID, diagnosis, notes, NULL AS appointment_ID, surgery_ID, NULL AS test_ID, patient_ID FROM medical_surgeries_data WHERE record_ID IS NOT NULL

UNION

SELECT record_ID, diagnosis, notes, NULL AS appointment_ID, NULL AS surgery_ID, test_ID, patient_ID FROM medical_tests_data WHERE record_ID IS NOT NULL;

Create prescription table

CREATE TABLE Prescription AS SELECT DISTINCT pb.prescription_ID, pb.record_ID, pb.pharmacy_ID, ma.patient_ID, a.professional_name, a.professional_role FROM prescription_billing_insurance_data pb JOIN medical_appointments_data ma ON pb.record_ID = ma.record_ID JOIN appointments_data a ON ma.appointment_ID = a.appointment_ID WHERE prescription_ID IS NOT NULL;

Model solution 1: Supervised Learning for Patient Readmission¶

Problem: The NHS faces challenges in efficiently allocating hospital resources and improving patient outcomes. One factor that could be causing this is frequent patient readmissions as it may strain healthcare resources, and often indicates suboptimal care. Early identification of patients at risk of readmission can support hospital administrators to ensure sufficient staffing and resources.

Solution: To address this, I developed a machine learning model to predict whether a patient is likely to be readmitted within 30 days of a previous visit, a critical window for intervention. The model uses logistic regression, which I will first attempt to train on the following features:

  • Visit results: Indicators of complications.
  • Visit type: Certain procedures have higher post-operative risks.
  • Patient gender: Some conditions are more prevalent in specific genders.
  • Age at visit: Recovery rates vary with age.
  • Diagnosis: Chronic conditions lead to repeated care.
  • Number of previous visits: Frequent visits indicate chronic issues.
  • Days since last visit: Short gaps may suggest ongoing health problems.

Justification: A logistic regression model works well where the goal is to predict a binary outcome (readmitted = 0 or not readmitted = 1). It provides coefficients that highlight the impact of each feature on the readmission probability which may aid clinical data informed decision making.

Step 1: Loading the necessary datasets to extract the input features required for the model. The extracted input features will be stored in the dataframe, dfVisit

# Adding revisited_within_30_days column into dfVisit

dfVisit = dfVisit.sort_values(by=["patient_ID", "visit_date"]).reset_index(drop=True)

dfVisit["revisited_within_30_days"] = 0  

# Calculates if a patient revisits in 30 days 
for i in range(len(dfVisit) - 1):
    # Check if the next visit for the same patient is within 30 days
    current_patient = dfVisit.loc[i, "patient_ID"]
    current_date = dfVisit.loc[i, "visit_date"]
    next_patient = dfVisit.loc[i + 1, "patient_ID"]
    next_date = dfVisit.loc[i + 1, "visit_date"]
    
    if current_patient == next_patient and (next_date - current_date).days <= 30:
        dfVisit.loc[i, "revisited_within_30_days"] = 1

Results:

The final Logistic Regression model (Model 3) used visit type, number of previous visits, days since last visit, and chronic flag as features. Initially, features like visit results, patient gender, age at visit, and diagnosis were considered but later excluded after their coefficients showed minimal impact, reducing potential noise.

The num_previous_visits emerged as the most influential feature (0.839), indicating patients with a higher number of previous visits are significantly more likely to be readmitted.

The model effectively predicted non-readmissions (Class 0) with 0.89 precision and 0.87 f1-score, but struggled with readmissions (Class 1), achieving only 0.51 precision and 0.55 f1-score.

Although this model improved over model 1 by addressing class imbalance, it showed comparable performance to model 2, even after adding the chronic flag. Therefore, this model can support the NHS in predicting patients that may not be readmitted but it may struggle to accurately identify patient readmissions.

Limitations:

The model remains sensitive to class imbalance. It lacks clinical features, limiting its ability to capture readmission risk accurately.

Model solution 2: Inferential Statistics for Analyzing Effectiveness of Medical Intervensions¶

Problem: The NHS aims to optimize patient outcomes and improve healthcare delivery across different hospital types. One way to investigate this is by questioning whether private hospital types typically achieve better surgical success rates than NHS hospitals, which could guide future resource allocation and quality improvement efforts, and reveal if the medical quality of NHS hospitals is lower than in private hospitals.

Solution: To analyze if the surgery outcomes differ from hospital type, I will randomly select 10 hospitals of NHS and private hospital type each, and use a Chi-Square Test of Independence to assess whether their surgical success rates differ significantly.

  • Null Hypothesis (H0): There is no significant difference in the proportion of successful surgery outcomes between NHS Hospitals and Private Hospitals, such that the success rates are independent of hospital type.

(H0: P of NHS Hospitals = P of Private Hospitals)

  • Alternative Hypothesis (H1): There is a significant difference in the proportion of successful surgery outcomes between NHS Hospitals and Private Hospitals, such that the success rates depend on the hospital type. (H1: P of NHS Hospitals != P of Private Hospitals)

Justification: The Chi-Square Test of Independence was chosen because it’s a non-parametric test which is suitable for categorical data (successful outcomes vs unsuccessful outcomes), which allows for comparison of proportions across groups without assuming a normal distribution.

Randomly sampling 10 hospitals from each type and selecting those with records of 200-500 surgeries ensures a fair and balanced comparison. This approach allows the analysis to avoid bias from extremely high or low surgery counts while maintaining adequate sample size for Chi-Square testing. Random sampling also helps reduce selection bias. Overall, it offers a representative selection of surgery outcomes across both hospital types without over generalising from a single hospital.

This suggests that the type of hospital (private vs NHS) does not significantly impact the likelihood of successful surgery outcomes, and so NHS hospitals are just as effective as private hospitals.

The test satisfies a key assumption of the Chi-Square Test where the minimum expected frequency in each cell is well above 5 (minimum expected frequency = 1040), ensuring the chi-square approximation is reliable. Thus, the conclusion drawn from this test is likely to be accurate.

# Visualizing the Chi-Square distribution curve 
from scipy.stats import chi2

#Significance level
alpha = 0.05

# Define range of x values 
x = np.linspace(0, 5, 500)
y = chi2.pdf(x, df=dof)

critical_value = chi2.ppf(1 - alpha, df=dof)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(x, y, label='Chi-Square Distribution (df=1)', color='blue')

# Shade the critical region (rejection region)
plt.fill_between(x, y, where=(x >= critical_value), color='red', alpha=0.4, label='Rejection Region (α=0.05)')

# Plot test statistic

Solution 3: Unsupervised Learning K-means Clustering¶

Problem: One potential application the NHS is exploring is identifying high-risk patients who may require more intensive monitoring. By recognising these patients early, the NHS can improve overall patient care and optimise resource allocation by prioritising those with greater needs. This also helps healthcare professionals avoid missing critical early intervention opportunities.

Solution: To address this, I used an unsupervised machine learning approach via K-Means clustering to segment patients based on their hospital visit patterns and clinical indicators.

The model uses features such as:

  • Number of total visits: High number of visits are more likely to have chronic conditions
  • Rate of hospital visits within 30 days : Frequent revisits within a month may indicate instability in a patient’s condition
  • Age: Older patients generally have higher risk to chronic illnesses
  • Average days since last hospital visit: Shorter intervals between visits may signal active treatment cycles or poor health management
  • Frequency of visits according to the visit type: Different visit types represent different levels of care intensity.
  • Presence of chronic conditions: Flags patients with long-term health risks.

Justification: Identifying high-risk patients which lack predefined labels makes this well-suited for an unsupervised learning approach. Instead of predicting a known risk score, the goal is to discover natural groupings in patient behaviour and clinical patterns that may indicate varying levels of risk which can be done by K-means clustering. It is also easy to interpret allowing stakeholders to understand characteristics of each cluster (high-risk vs low-risk patients).

Results:

Cluster 0: Low risk patients

  • Low number of hospital visits (averages at 1) and very rarely revisits
  • Almost no tests or surgeries (mostly appointments, no surgery visit type)
  • Only about 14% of patients has had a history of chronic diseases

Cluster 1: Moderate risk patients

  • Moderate number of hospital visits (averages at 3) and at and average will revisit in 55 days (about 2 months gap)
  • Has record of having a mix of appointment, surgery and test visit types but at low frequencies (Averages at 2 appointment visits, and 0 or 1 appointment/test visits)
  • About 38% of patients has had a history of chronic diseases

Cluster 2: High risk patients

  • Frequent hospital visits (15+)
  • Very high revisit within 30 days rate (78%)
  • Has had high number of tests (13+), over surgeries and appointments
  • Almost all patients have chronic diseases (99%)

Thus, this enables the NHS to prioritize patients that fall in cluster 2 for more intensive monitoring and proactive care, potentially to improve patient outcomes. Patients in cluster 1 may also benefit from targeted management for early intervention to prevent future complications or readmissions.

Limitations:

Chronic flag labels were based on assumption from a small set of lists provided by the NHS website rather than true clinical records that were not provided in given data, thus may misclassify certain conditions. Additionally, the model assumes patients with similar metrics share similar risk profiles, which may not capture rare or outlier cases.

Task 4: Ethics and Analysis (10 Marks)¶

I. (5 marks) Discuss the ethical implications of your modelling solutions given in Task 3. How can these ethical challenges be mitigated in a real-world NHS setting? Your answer to this question must not exceed 200 words.

Across all three models, 2 ethical principles most at risk involve fairness and accountability. In the patient readmission prediction model and the clustering of high risk patients model, relying on features like chronic condition flag may unfairly disadvantage patients with pre-existing conditions by disproportionately flagging them as high risk. These models risk misclassifying patients as high-risk based on incomplete or assumed data, potentially overlooking other at-risk individuals who may also be likely to be readmitted. The NHS vs private hospital comparison model risks stigmatizing NHS hospitals if it overlooks contextual factors such as patient complexity or surgeon experience, which differs in both hospitals, thus may produce unfair results when compared.

To mitigate these risks, models should be audited regularly for bias, particularly across protected groups, and developed in consultation with clinicians to ensure medically relevant and fair interpretations. Outputs should support and not replace clinical judgment, and any patient flagged by the model should be subject to professional review.

Moreover, since medical data falls under the “special category” in GDPR, it must be anonymised, securely stored, and used with informed consent. Even if data processing here is justified for vital or public interest, transparency remains essential.

    INSTR(SUBSTR(hospital_location, INSTR(hospital_location, ',') + 1), ',') - 1
  )) AS city,
  COUNT(*) AS hospital_count
FROM hospital
GROUP BY city;
"""

# Store the result in dataframe

b) For each hospital, its name, city, the number of departments, and the number of patients who prefer that hospital, using outer join. Sort the hospitals within each city by the number of preferred patients in descending order.

In [769]:
con = sqlite3.connect("DATA Assessment.db")

query = """
WITH hospital_city AS (
    SELECT
        hospital_ID,
        hospital_name,
        TRIM(SUBSTR(
            hospital_location,
            INSTR(hospital_location, ',') + 1,
            INSTR(SUBSTR(hospital_location, INSTR(hospital_location, ',') + 1), ',') - 1
        )) AS city
    FROM hospital
),

department_count AS (
    SELECT
        hospital_ID,
        COUNT(*) AS department_sum
    FROM department
    GROUP BY hospital_ID
),

patient_preferred_hospital_count AS (
    SELECT
        patient_preferred_hospital_ID AS hospital_ID,
        COUNT(*) AS num_preferred_patients
    FROM patient
    GROUP BY patient_preferred_hospital_ID
)

SELECT 
    h.hospital_name,
    h.city,
    d.department_sum,
    p.num_preferred_patients
FROM hospital_city h
LEFT JOIN department_count d ON h.hospital_ID = d.hospital_ID
LEFT JOIN patient_preferred_hospital_count p ON h.hospital_ID = p.hospital_ID
ORDER BY h.city, p.num_preferred_patients DESC;
"""

df_result = pd.read_sql_query(query, con)

con.close()

df_result
